29 Sec. 5. 1. The Legislature hereby finds and declares that:
30 (a) Section 9 of Article 8 of the Nevada Constitution contains a provision
31 commonly known as a “gift clause” which restricts the State under certain
32 circumstances from donating or loaning the State’s money or credit to any
33 company, association or corporation, except corporations formed for educational or
34 charitable purposes.
35 (b) In Employers Insurance Company of Nevada v. State Board of Examiners,
36 117 Nev. 249, 258 (2001), the Nevada Supreme Court held that the State loans its
37 credit in violation of Section 9 of Article 8 of the Nevada Constitution only when
38 “the State acts as a surety or guarantor for the debts of a company, corporation or
39 association.”
40 (c) In Lawrence v. Clark County, 127 Nev. 390, 399 (2011), the Nevada
41 Supreme Court held that the State does not donate, loan or “gift” its money in
42 violation of Section 9 of Article 8 of the Nevada Constitution when the State
43 dispenses state funds for a public purpose and the State receives a valuable benefit
44 or fair consideration in exchange for the dispensation of the state funds.
45 (d) In State ex rel. Brennan v. Bowman, 89 Nev. 330, 333 (1973), the Nevada
46 Supreme Court held that legislation which promotes economic development and
47 seeks to create, protect or enhance job opportunities “inures to the public benefit”
48 and serves important public purposes because it assists in “relieving unemployment
49 and maintaining a stable economy.”
50 (e) In Lawrence v. Clark County, 127 Nev. 390, 399, 406 (2011), the Nevada
51 Supreme Court adopted the public trust doctrine in this State, noting that the public
52 possesses inviolable rights to the natural resources of the State and the State must
53 serve as trustee of the public resources and finding that the “constitutional policy

