1 contained in the gift clause infers the people’s intent to constrain the Legislature’s
2 ability to alienate public trust lands as well as public funds.”
3 (f) Section 3 of Article 9 of the Nevada Constitution restricts the ability of the
4 State to contract public debts, but makes an exception for “any and all contracts
5 necessary, expedient or advisable for the protection and preservation of any of its
6 property or natural resources, or for the purposes of obtaining the benefits thereof,”
7 which further emphasizes the constitutionally mandated importance of the
8 protection and preservation of the natural resources of this State.
9 (g) In McLaughlin v. Housing Authority of the City of Las Vegas, 68 Nev. 84,
10 93 (1951) and Lawrence v. Clark County, 127 Nev. 390, 399 (2011), the Nevada
11 Supreme Court held that when the Legislature authorizes a state agency to dispense
12 state funds, the courts will:
13 (1) Carefully examine whether the Legislature made an informed and
14 appropriate finding that the dispensation of the state funds serves a public purpose
15 and the State receives a valuable benefit or fair consideration in exchange for the
16 dispensation;
17 (2) Give great weight and due deference to the Legislature’s finding, and
18 the courts will uphold the Legislature’s “finding unless it clearly appears to be
19 erroneous and without reasonable foundation;” and
20 (3) Closely examine whether the dispensing state agency reviews all facts,
21 figures and necessary information when making the dispensation, and when the
22 state agency has done so, it will not be second-guessed by the courts.
23 2. The Legislature hereby further finds and declares that:
24 (a) The release of greenhouse gases traps heat in the Earth’s atmosphere,
25 driving climate change.
26 (b) The United States Environmental Protection Agency has concluded that
27 certain large subsonic jet aircraft and subsonic propeller driven airplanes that are
28 used in all domestic and international flights originating in the United States are
29 responsible for 10 percent of all greenhouse gas emissions from the transportation
30 sector in the United States and 3 percent of all greenhouse gas emissions in the
31 United States.
32 (c) According to the Federal Aviation Administration, about 10 percent of all
33 aircraft emissions occur close to the surface of the Earth near ground level and most
34 particulate matter that affects communities surrounding an airport are the result of
35 emissions released during landing and takeoff.
36 (d) Climate change threatens the health, lives and safety of Nevada’s residents,
37 as well as Nevada’s diverse ecosystems, wildlands and wildlife. Rising
38 temperatures have increased the severity and length of droughts and the frequency
39 and intensity of wildfires.
40 (e) Climate change threatens Nevada’s economy. Rising temperatures,
41 compounded by the urban heat island effect, will likely make summers in Southern
42 Nevada dangerously hot, potentially deterring visitors and reducing the hours when
43 it is safe to engage in outdoor activities, such as construction.
44 (f) Throughout this State, rising temperatures will impact public health by
45 increasing heat stress on vulnerable populations and increasing air pollution from
46 more frequent wildfires.
47 (g) The State of Nevada and its residents will benefit from the diversification
48 and economic growth driven by a transition to a low-carbon emission aviation
49 transportation sector.
50 3. The Legislature lastly finds and declares that:
51 (a) The state program developed and carried into effect pursuant to this act will
52 not result in the State acting as a surety or guarantor of the debts of an air carrier
53 receiving an incentive of money.

